"1323":"1323","1322":"1322","1376":"1376","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","about 1334":"circa 1334","1308":"1308","1328":"1328",", Surrey, England":"Surrey, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Gatton, Surrey, England":"Gatton, Surrey, England","Mahlberg, Kent, England":"Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1325–1376":"1325–1376","1308–Male":"1308–Deceased","1322–1374":"1322–1374","1323–Female":"1323–Deceased","1310–1360":"1310–1360","1310–1370":"1310–1370","1335–Female":"1335–Deceased","1280–1328":"1280–1328","1374":"1374","Abt 1335":"about 1335","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1280":"1280","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","17 July 1360":"17 July 1360","1335":"1335","1323":"1323","1322":"1322","1376":"1376","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","about 1334":"about 1334","1308":"1308","1328":"1328",", Surrey, England":"Surrey, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Gatton, Surrey, England":"Gatton, Surrey, England","Mahlberg, Kent, England":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Denne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Denn  .","French (mainly northern) and Walloon: probably a variant of <b>Dhenne</b>, a patronymic, with fused preposition <i>d(e)</i> ‘of’, from <i>Henne</i>, a pet form of the personal names French <i>Henri</i>, Flemish <i>Hendrik</i> (see   Henry   1). Alternatively, perhaps a variant of <b>Daine</b>, the feminine form of   Dain  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Denn","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Denne  , a habitational name from one or more of the numerous places in Kent and Sussex with names derived from Middle English <i>den</i> ‘woodland swine-pasture’ (Old English <i>denn</i>), such as Denne Manor in Chilham, Denne Hill in Kingston, and Denne Court in Woodnesborough (Kent); Denne Park in Horsham, Denne in Warnham, and Dann's Farm in Willingdon (Sussex).","English: possibly from a pet form of   Denis  ."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":3,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":12,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Elizabeth De Denne was born in 1325, in Kent, England as the daughter of Walter Denne. She married Robert De Northwode about 1334, in Gatton, Surrey, England. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. She died in 1376, in England, at the age of 51."},"et":{"1325–1376":"1325–1376","1308–Male":"1308–Surnud","1322–1374":"1322–1374","1323–Female":"1323–Surnud","1310–1360":"1310–1360","1310–1370":"1310–1370","1335–Female":"1335–Surnud","1280–1328":"1280–1328","1374":"1374","Abt 1335":"umbes 1335","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1280":"1280","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","17 July 1360":"17. juuli 1360","1335":"1335","1323":"1323","1322":"1322","1376":"1376","1453":"1453","1310":"1310","about 1334":"umbes 1334","1308":"1308","1328":"1328",", Surrey, England":"Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Kent, England":"Kent, England","Gatton, Surrey, England":"Gatton, Surrey, England","Mahlberg, Kent, England":"Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1325–1376":"1325–1376","1308–Male":"1308–Kuollut","1322–1374":"1322–1374","1323–Female":"1323–Kuollut","1310–1360":"1310–1360","1310–1370":"1310–1370","1335–Female":"1335–Kuollut","1280–1328":"1280–1328","1374":"1374","Abt 1335":"noin 1335","1360":"1360","1370":"1370","1280":"1280","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","17 July 1360":"17. heinäkuuta 1360","1335":"1335","1323":"1323","1322":"1322","1376":"1376","1